m any of several places called Barlow, especially those in Lancashire and Yorkshire. The former is named with Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘hill’; the latter probably has as its first element the derived adjective <i>beren</i> or the compound <i>bere-ærn</i> ‘barn’. There is also a place of this name in Derbyshire, named with Old English <i>bār</i> ‘boar’ or <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, and one in Shropshire, which is from <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Barlowe","meanings":["English: variant of   Barlow  ."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"James Barlow was born about 1082, in Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Thomas Barlow and Mrs Barlow. He married Miss Worsley about 1112, in Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt. 1082–":"umbes 1082–Surnud","1082–Male":"1082–Surnud","1086–1140":"1086–1140","1113–1173":"1113–1173","1051–Male":"1051–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","Abt. 1082":"umbes 1082","Abt 1112":"umbes 1112","1113":"1113","ABT 1113":"umbes 1113","1086":"1086","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1051":"1051","1082":"1082","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt. 1082–":"noin 1082–Kuollut","1082–Male":"1082–Kuollut","1086–1140":"1086–1140","1113–1173":"1113–1173","1051–Male":"1051–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","Abt. 1082":"noin 1082","Abt 1112":"noin 1112","1113":"1113","ABT 1113":"noin 1113","1086":"1086","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1051":"1051","1082":"1082","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt. 1082–":"environ 1082–Décédé","1082–Male":"1082–Décédé","1086–1140":"1086–1140","1113–1173":"1113–1173","1051–Male":"1051–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","Abt. 1082":"environ 1082","Abt 1112":"environ 1112","1113":"1113","ABT 1113":"environ 1113","1086":"1086","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1051":"1051","1082":"1082","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"James Barlow est né environ 1082, à Chorlton, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Sir Thomas Barlow et Mrs Barlow. Il a épousé Miss Worsley environ 1112, à Chorlton, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"Abt. 